description: From Middle French ramification, or its source, Latin ramificō.

entries.meaning: (botany, anatomy) A branching-out, the act or result of developing branches; specifically the divergence of the stem and limbs of a plant into smaller ones, or of similar developments in blood vessels, anatomical structures etc.
examples: The character of trees may be studied to advantage  […]  in winter, when the forms of the ramification can be seen in the naked boughs  […]

entries.meaning: An offshoot of a decision, fact etc.; a consequence or implication, especially one which complicates a situation.
examples: The treachery of some of the Jacobite agents (Rashleigh among the rest), and the arrest of others, had made George the First's Government acquainted with the extensive ramifications of a conspiracy long prepared, and which at last exploded prematurely  […]
